    "human D vicuna D llama D chatgpt Average Zero-Shot (No FT) LLaMA 33.51 24.71 31.46 20.09 27.44 ChatGPT 10.26 31.93 48.36 43.84 33.61 FT on all data FT-All (BERT) 77.50 71.69 69.48 87.21 76.47 w/ DELD 94.42 80.64 81.94 92.45 87.36 FT-All (T5) 79.42 73.45 74.36 86.35 78.39 w/ DELD 96.12 83.35 85.24 92.10 89.20 FT a model per dataset FT-Per (BERT) 74.09 77.29 68.97 87.21 76.89 w/ DELD 93.61 89.52 82.63 91.78 89.39 FT-Per (T5) 77.30 77.38 69.20 91.37 78.81 w/ DELD 98.75 84.34 89.77 92.58 91.36 FT on sequential datasets FT-Seq (BERT) 69.62 66.27 74.65 83.11 73.40 w/ DELD 82.71 81.93 78.87 97.26 85.19 FT-Seq (T5) 72.53 71.84 77.31 86.10 76.95 w/ DELD 91.20 86.71 86.10 97.81 90.44 detection across different datasets: D human, D vicuna, D llama, and D chatgpt.Our method, DELD, demonstrated superior performance across various experimental settings.",
    "The main findings from our experiments are summarized as follows:• Zero-Shot (No FT): The models without any finetuning showed significantly lower performance across all datasets.",
    "Specifically, ChatGPT (GPT-4) achieved an average accuracy of 33.61%, while the LLaMA model achieved 27.44%.",
    "• Fine-tuning on All Data: The FT-All setting, where the model was trained on the combined data from all datasets, resulted in a substantial improvement, with an average accuracy of 76.47% for BERT and 78.39% for T5.",
    "When enhanced with DELD, the accuracy further increased, achieving 87.36% and 89.20% for BERT and T5, respectively."
